Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Kenya Commercial Bank, Omnicane Move

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-16T16:01:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-16/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-fidelity-bank-omnicane-of-mauritius-are-active.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for a
second day, adding 0.3 percent to 62.21 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  fell for the first day
in four, retreating 0.5 percent, to 775.06 by the 4 p.m. close
in Windhoek. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index
advanced 1 percent to 22,729.06 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos,
according to a statement on the  bourse’s website . Mauritius’s
SEMDEX Index rose for a third day, adding 0.1 percent to
1,955.83 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index gained 0.2 percent to 1,178.76 by the 3
p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd. (KNCB)  , the country’s third-
biggest lender by market value, rose for the first time in three
days, adding 25 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 21 shillings.
Yesterday, the stock’s 14-day relative strength index closed at
26, below the 30 level that signals to some technical analysts a
security is poised to increase.  Omnicane Ltd. (MTMD)  , a Mauritian sugar producer with
interests in energy, rose to its highest in a month, advancing 1
rupee, or 1.4 percent, to 72.50 rupees. The company said its
loss narrowed to 56.8 million rupees ($2 million) in the three
months through June compared with 176.5 million rupees a year
earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
